{
    "node_id": "time-matrix-21",
    "title": "Projecting Data: Future Perfect",
    "description": "Talking about things that will be completed by a specific time in the future.",
    "display_order": 21,
    "prerequisites": ["time-matrix-20"],
    "lesson_content_markdown": "# Projecting Data: Future Perfect\n\nWhen we talk about the future in research, we often project that something will be **finished** by a certain time. We use the **Future Perfect** for this.\n\n### 1. The Timeline\nImagine it is 2024 now. You plan to finish your university degree in 2026.\n- **Point in Future**: 2026.\n- **Completed Action**: Finishing the degree.\n- **The Sentence**: *\"By 2026, I **will have finished** my degree.\"*\n\n### 2. How to Make It\nUse **will have** + the **Past Participle** (V3).\n\n- **Formula**: Subject + will have + V3 (e.g., finished, discovered, moved)\n- **Example**: By next month, the science team **will have analyzed** all the samples.\n\n### 3. Common Keyword: \"By\"\nWe almost always use **by** or **by the time** with the Future Perfect to show the deadline.\n- **Example**: **By 2050**, the world population **will have grown** by two billion people.\n- **Example**: **By the time** you arrive, I **will have cooked** dinner.\n\n### 4. Why use it?\nIt helps you talk about **goals** and **results** in the future, not just actions that are happening.\n\n---",
